        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">Another comparison for you.  How many people have manuals describing the game, listing all the stats, detailed maps, item locations for EQ or any other game?  Is this not the same thing as buying an item?  You spend the money for knowledge or an item to avoid the time wasted finding it out yourself or getting the item yourself.  Someone put a ton of work into making all those maps, detailing where all those items are, and you drop $20 to buy the book.  Same idea... someone puts a ton of work into getting the everpopular FBSS and you drop $20 to buy it.  In both cases, the game is promoted, both parties are happy, and money is spent for time.</P><P>It makes NO sense to argue the line between fantasy and reality when you pay $10 a month just to play the game.  The only thing to consider is the entertainment factor, if that's unethical you have serious problems.  You PAY for entertainment, why is this such a hard concept to grasp?  Tons of people make money of EQ besides VI, so there's no argument there either (see all profit websites), if you think that's unethical talk to advertisers.  </P><P>Nah, it's a simple matter of jealousy by the extremely high level people who have 30 hours to put into a game.  VI caters to those people, they are after all their bread and butter.</P><P>ZZ</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
