        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">Have to agree with Wakawaka here. He probably bought my old account.</P><P>Here's the way my E-bay experience went. I had leveled a warrior up to 35. But I could no longer afford to devote the 3-5+ hours straight that you need to play if you want to group. I needed to have a solo option. So I wanted to switch to a necro (or mage or shaman or druid). I'm what I would call a "casual" player.</P><P>I knew I wouldn't be playing the warrior anymore, so I decided to auction the account. Now, I could've parceled things off and sold them separately, but I just didn't want to be bothered. So I sold it bulk to someone who I got the distinct feeling was going to strip the character for parts.</P><P>I was happy. I made $350 for the character. The buyer was happy. I'm sure he resold it for lots more cash. His buyers were happy, they got the items they wanted without ever needed to spend the time camping them. Others wanting to earn the items in game should have been happy because they had fewer people with whom to compete for the camp.</P><P>The only people who potentially were unhappy were the mindless E-Bay whiners who don't care much about the details. They hear that someone recovered some cash off EQ or that someone is playing a Level 35 warrior without having "earned " the level and it somehow ruins their day.</P><P>Why? For that answer you'' have to talk to a psychologist.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
